  "dimensions": {
    "relational_environment": {
      "present": true,
      "note": "All four rings active. Ring 1 dominates. Ring 2 substantially present: God remembers, commands remembering, searches minds, renews the mind, writes law on the dianoia, gives the mind of Christ, relents/changes his own mind (na.cham), and defines himself as one who plans and purposes (boulē, ya.tsar). Ring 3 present through shared-mind vocabulary, remembrance in prayer for others, comfort/consolation (na.cham/G), and conscience in community. Ring 4 is marginal but present through noēma: Satan's designs on the mind (2Cor 2:11) and blinding of minds (2Cor 4:4)."
    },
    "spirit_soul_body": {
      "present": true,
      "note": "Mind operates primarily at soul-level in the sense of the animating, inner personal centre — the seat of intentions, thoughts, and memory. Spirit-level engagement explicit in 1Cor 14:14-15 where Paul distinguishes praying with my spirit from praying with my mind (nous), indicating the nous operates at a level distinct from the pneuma. Body appears as instrument and as marker of mind-states."
    },
    "inner_operations": {
      "present": true,
      "note": "Full range documented: remembers and forgets; plans and devises; inclines and orients; evaluates from within (suneidēsis); changes (metanoeō, metamellomai, na.cham/H); collapses into madness (mainomai, ha.lal) or is maintained in sobriety (sōfroneō, nēfō); attends deliberately (H8104J). The most distinctive inner operation is renewal: transformation of the mind's fundamental orientation (Rom 12:2), which is divine action on the inner person."
    },
    "being": {
      "present": true,
      "note": "Ye.tser (formed inclination) is the primary Hebrew term for the dispositional substrate of inner life. Sōfrōn family documents formed character of sound-mindedness. Froneō in Philippians operates as a characterising disposition. Conscience, once trained or damaged, operates as a formed inner capacity. The mind of Christ (1Cor 2:16) is the supreme example: not a moment of insight but a transferred orientation of being."
    }
  },
